<br>
At level 5, I left Felwithe to explore other places, a friend of mine named Cabot (a 35 wizard at the time, later given the Wizard Artifact of TP) teleported me from Felwithe to Erudin, where I picked up my new fashion robe and my Gloves of the Gatecaller (so awesome at the time)<br>
<br>
Actually, now that I remember I had to kill that necromancer Elial Brooke about a hundred times before I had good enough faction to do the quest.<br>
<br>
I know most of these people say that faction isn't really important, but raising factions can be a fun part of the game.  As a high elf, I'm max ally in the evil Necromancer/Shadowknight/Cleric Erudite city of Paineel.  I'm well liked in Freeport, and the Corrupt Guards in Qeynos love me.  Gnomes tolerate me and the Barbarians don't make quite as much fun of me anymore (Amiable to the Warrior faction).  The Claws of Veeshan consider me their ally as do the Dain's Dwarfs in Thurgadin.  Giants and Dark Elfs, for the most part, don't care for me much though... I might have killed a few too many of their guards <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
A lot of people take the easy route by killing guards for money and exp in various cities, but be sure you weigh the potential consequences before wrecking your faction.  This applys to hunting in some high level zones too, like the Plane of Growth.  Fighting here will give you major faction hits against Tunare, which is a bad thing for a High Elf.  There are some great quests in PoG too, but... well you have a long way to go.<br>
<br>
Most factions are repairable, some are not.  Make sure you know what you're doing <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
Good luck, and safe journies! <p>FREE US FROM THE DAMN HTML BAN!!!!<br>
<br>
Andara Lan`Gstrom<br>
53 Evoking Mage<br>
